user/description: Dedicated to the wonderful fashion/makeup/people/culture of the 20th century. Contact: livingthehistorylife@gmail.com
full_text:
Mustache cups from the Victorian era (1837-1901) in the United Kingdom.⁣
⁣
The device sat inside the cup and allowed one to drink from it while keeping their mustache dry. It was invented in the 1860s by British potter, Harvey Adams.⁣
⁣
Mustaches were extremely popular during the Victorian era. So much so that the British military mandated all its soldiers to grow one from 1860 to 1916. These soldiers would often apply mustache wax which kept all the facial hairs tidy and in place. Drinking hot liquids like tea or coffee would often melt the wax, which would then slowly drip into the cup. Mustache stains were also another major concern for coffee/tea drinkers during this time.⁣
⁣
The 1860 book "Gentlemen’s Book of Etiquette and Manual of Politeness" declared that mustaches must “never be curled, nor pulled out to an absurd length. Still worse is it to cut them close with the scissors. The mustache should be neat and not too large.”⁣
⁣
French writer, Guy de Maupassant (1850-1893) once said, “A man without a mustache is no longer a man,” and noted that their kisses “have no flavor, none whatever!”⁣
⁣
Starting in World War 1, soldiers began to shave their mustaches instead of trying to groom them while living in the trenches. Production for these cups continued to decline after the war as mustaches began to go out of fashion.⁣

full_text:
Good morning my fellow Canadians. This glorious morning, let's delve deeper into an unfolding story in Canada that I suspect has some lessons for us all. It's a political storm centered around the David Johnston report and its aftermath. The talk of the town now is that the Liberal Party is considering, get this, welcoming Han Dong back into their fold. I say, bring it on. Nothing like a little drama to spice things up, right?

But first, let's set the stage. We're talking about Han Dong here, but who exactly is this guy, and why does he matter? In case you've missed the headlines, let me get you up to speed. Global News, backed by two solid national security sources, has shone a spotlight on Dong with some allegations that, frankly, are quite concerning. And these claims, folks, are tied up with a story we all know too well - the saga of the "Two Michaels".

Yes, I'm talking about Michael Kovrig and Michael Spavor, two of our fellow Canadians who were entangled in an international diplomatic row, held captive by China. Many believe their detainment was an act of retaliation following Canada's arrest of Huawei executive Meng Wanzhou in 2018. It's a tale of international intrigue that's gripped the nation for years.

What's Dong's role in this, you ask? Well, he allegedly suggested to Han Tao, China's consul general in Toronto, that the release of the Two Michaels be delayed. And why would he advise such a thing? The answer, my friends, is as old as politics itself - to disadvantage the Opposition Conservatives. He's also accused of suggesting that Beijing demonstrate some progress on the Michaels' case - a ploy, it seems, designed to bolster the image of the ruling Liberal Party amidst public anger over China's treatment of the detained Canadians.

Of course, Dong has confirmed his discussion with Han but he vehemently denies these allegations. He insists that he advocated for the immediate release of the Two Michaels. Interesting, isn't it, that he only revealed this conversation to the Prime Minister's Office when media started to probe?

And, here's where the tale gets even murkier. According to former Governor General David Johnston - a man well familiar with the political labyrinth of Canada - Han Dong, during his re-election campaign in 2021, was persistently "maintaining close relationships" with China’s Consulate in Toronto. However, Dong is steadfast in his claim that he was never "informed" or would he "accept any help from a foreign country". Quite a puzzling contradiction, wouldn't you say? Especially given that his Liberal nomination campaign had quite an impressive turnout with busloads of students and seniors enthusiastically rallying behind him.

Now, this is where the intrigue takes a sharp turn. Dong himself admits in a court filing to having at least twelve - yes, twelve - phone calls with Communist Chinese diplomats. And we're not talking about low-level functionaries here. No, we're talking about Beijing’s Ambassador to Canada. He brushes it off as "common practice" for any Member of Parliament. Now, call me old-fashioned, but that sounds like an uncommonly curious practice to me. It does beg the question - just how frequently is our political leadership hopping on calls with foreign consulates? The Canadian people have a right to know. 

Let's be clear, the David Johnston report may have some interesting findings, but it certainly doesn't vindicate Dong. Despite the report mentioning "irregularities" in Han Dong's 2019 nomination for the federal Liberals, it still raises well-grounded suspicions of ties to the People's Republic of China consulate in Toronto. The report did not find concrete evidence that Dong was aware of these irregularities or the consulate's potential involvement, but it doesn't mean he's completely cleared of any wrongdoing.

A public inquiry is absolutely essential to bring clarity and transparency to the controversies surrounding Han Dong. With so many allegations and suspicions circulating about his alleged ties to the Chinese consulate and the irregularities in his nomination, it's crucial that we have a thorough and independent investigation to get to the truth.

The Canadian public deserves to know the full extent of any potential foreign interference in our democratic processes. A public inquiry would provide a platform for all the evidence to be presented, witnesses to be heard, and any hidden agendas to be exposed. This is the only way to ensure that the truth prevails and that justice is served.

Imagine, if you will, the scene of a public inquiry. The room is packed with observers, journalists, and politicians from all parties. The air is electric with anticipation. The collective gaze is focused on one man, standing alone in the center of the stage. This man is Han Dong.

As he stands in the spotlight, a strange calm descends upon him. The reality of the situation is settling in. He is here, center stage, about to testify before a public inquiry. There is no turning back now. The questions will come hard and fast, and all of Canada - indeed, the world - will be watching.

The chairman, a stern and experienced legal mind, opens the proceedings. The questions begin. About the Blacklock's reports, the dozen calls with Communist Chinese diplomats, the close relationships with China’s Consulate in Toronto during the 2021 re-election campaign. Each question is a hammer blow, each answer a potential landmine.

"Mr. Dong," the chairman begins, "Can you explain these continuous contacts with Chinese diplomats? And what about the allegations of advising a delay in the release of the Two Michaels? What did you mean by 'common practice' for an MP? How many of your colleagues maintain such frequent contact with the Chinese consulate?"

The room holds its breath as Dong begins his answers. He denies, he sidesteps, he redirects. But the chairman is relentless, pushing for clarity, for truth. The audience, rapt in attention, follows the verbal dance, waiting for the stumble, the slip that will reveal the truth.

This, my friends, is what a public inquiry with real subpoena power looks like. It's the antithesis of political rhetoric or evasion. It's a quest for truth. And if the Trudeau government had nothing to hide, why would they delay such an inquiry?

Now, let's dwell a bit on this notion. "What does it tell you about a government that avoids transparency?" The answer, I believe, is something that many Canadians are slowly beginning to comprehend.

In a healthy democracy, the government is held accountable by its citizens. That accountability is largely dependent on transparency. Without transparency, there is no accountability. Without accountability, there is no democracy. So when a government actively avoids transparency, one can't help but wonder: What are they trying to hide?

Let's remember, the Trudeau government is not delaying just any inquiry; they're stalling an inquiry into allegations of serious misconduct within their own ranks. Allegations that, if proven, could be not only politically damaging, but criminally culpable.

Is it fear that propels this reticence? Fear of what the inquiry may uncover? Fear of the political fallout? Fear of the potential legal repercussions? It would seem so.

And if that is the case, if there are facts being obscured, if there are truths being avoided, then that is a disquieting indication of a government more concerned with self-preservation than with the wellbeing of its people. It is a flagrant contradiction of the principles of accountability and transparency upon which a democratic society is built.

A government's duty is to serve its citizens, not its own political interests. Its actions should be motivated by the public good, not by the fear of political or personal ramifications. If a government is more concerned with avoiding scrutiny than with serving its people, then it's clear that the principles of democracy are being undermined.

The Trudeau government's hesitance to move forward with this inquiry is deeply troubling. It's a clear indicator that something is not quite right in the halls of power in Ottawa. And it's high time that the Canadian people were given the truth.

Now, the question is, will the Trudeau administration have the courage to face the music and deliver transparency to the people who gave them power? Or will they continue to stall, to obfuscate, to undermine the democratic process for their own ends?

So let's call a spade a spade. This is not just about a single politician or a single party. This is about preserving the integrity of our democracy. This is about holding our elected officials accountable, regardless of their political affiliation. This is about demanding transparency and the truth. This is about Canada, our home.

So yes, I welcome the inquiry. In fact, I implore it. It's not a matter of partisanship, it's a matter of principle. And if anyone - be they Liberal, Conservative, or otherwise - has knowingly benefited from foreign interference in our democratic processes, then they need to be held accountable.

This isn't a game. If proven true, these are acts that undermine the very foundation of our democracy, and the punishment should fit the crime. Treason might seem like a harsh word, but let's not shy away from calling it what it is. If individuals, from Han Dong to Justin Trudeau, have conspired with foreign powers to influence our elections, they have betrayed their country and their fellow Canadians.

There's a lot at stake here, folks. More than political careers or party fortunes. This is about the soul of our nation. We owe it to ourselves, and to future generations of Canadians, to ensure that our democracy remains strong, free, and uncompromised.

So let's demand the inquiry. Let's demand the truth. Let's insist that our government, regardless of who's in power, remains transparent and accountable to the people they serve. Let's ensure that anyone who betrays that trust is held accountable. That's the Canadian way. That's our way.

Stay vigilant, Canada. Keep demanding the truth. Because this inquiry is not just important, it's essential!

user/description: Daily history lessons. Education through memes!
full_text:
The Stadium of Aphrodisias, Asia Minor (Turkey) is considered the best preserved stadium in the Mediterranean. With a length of 262 meters, a width of 59 meters and a capacity of 30,000 spectators on 22 rows of seats, it is also one of the largest of its kind.

Unlike, for example, the construction of the Perge stadium (also one of the largest stadiums in Asia Minor), the substructure of the rows of seats was largely made up of mounds of earth. This is an indication that the original building of the stadium was already built in Hellenistic times. Another special feature of this stadium is that it is closed on both narrow sides. Thus it differs clearly from the mostly horseshoe-shaped stadiums of the Roman Empire.

The athletes entered the arena through a tunnel embedded in the narrow sides of the stadium. Above the western entrance tunnel was the emperor's box, from where he opened the games held in his honor.

The stadium was originally crowned by a circumferential portico (colonnade). Holes in the rows of seats and supporting stones on the outside of the portico testify to the existence of a sunscreen. The spectators reached their seats from the outside via staircases and were distributed over the portico.

In Hellenistic times, sports such as wrestling, boxing, discus and javelin throwing as well as running competitions found a wide audience.

“First, by bidding goodbye to clerical control of domestic decision-making, Saudi Arabia is no longer a theocratic state, rather moving towards a more vibrant society that is inclusive… Second, the Muslim World’s politics was defined for the past four decades by an ideological foreign policy of Saudi Arabia with its triangular mixture of money, militancy and madrassas, often peddling conflicts… That phase has now come to an end, which is very positive for peace, stability and harmony in the Muslim World. Oleg Tinkov the Russian Billionaire with a potted history of principles. Inspired by tax exile RIchard Branson and indicted fraudster, Donald Trump. Quietly un-sanctioned in July 2023.

The United Kingdom has removed sanctions on Russian billionaire Oleg Tinkov, who has called Moscow's war against Ukraine "crazy," and renounced his Russian citizenship in November last year. Tinkov's name disappeared from Britain’s' sanctions list on July 20 without explanation.

Oleg Yuryevich Tinkov is a Russian-born Cypriot entrepreneur and businessman. Tinkov is one of Russia’s best-known entrepreneurs and founded Tinkoff Bank in 2006. He has been based outside Russia in recent years. The Western sanctions on him and other top Russian business figures - known as "oligarchs" - include travel bans, asset freezes and impounding of planes and yachts. President Putin's political and military power relies heavily on the support of billionaires, who got rich through Kremlin connections.

Forbes and Forbes Russia do not consider Oleg Tinkov to be an oligarch, despite him having been sanctioned: "Tinkov is not an oligarch because he built an independent fortune without ties to the Russian government under either Boris Yeltsin or Vladimir Putin". per Wikipedia.

In 2019 Tinkov was diagnosed with leukemia.Tinkov was indicted by a US grand jury in Sept 2019 for willfully filing false tax returns and attempting to evade over $240 million in taxes while renouncing his US citizenship. He was arrested in London in February 2020 but fought extradition based on a new diagnosis of leukaemia making him too unwell to travel. He eventually pleaded guilty and was sentenced to pay over $508 million in unpaid taxes, fines and a fraud penalty, as well as time served and a year's supervised release.

In March 2023, it became known that Tinkov appealed to the British government with a request to lift sanctions from him. He said he welcomed "the decision to put on the sanctions list people who support Vladimir Putin or contribute to the war," but said he did not consider himself such a person. Tinkov has long been living abroad. Since 1996, he had, in addition to Russian, US citizenship, which he refused in 2013, at the same time as he became a billionaire. Now he has Cypriot citizenship.

The UK Foreign Office said that Tinkov would no longer be subject to sanctions following an appeal during which he argued the UK had sanctioned him in error and enlisted the support of #RichardBranson as well as Mikhail Khodorkovsky, a major opponent of the Russian president, to make his case. Whereas most Russian oligarchs have spoken out against the invasion only in guarded terms, Tinkov has denounced the “crazy war” in Ukraine and renounced his Russian citizenship last year in protest. “While he was a wealthy Russian businessman he has never been an oligarch,” Branson, who Tinkov often cited as his inspiration, wrote in a statement cited by the Times earlier this week. “I have always known him as a self-made dynamic entrepreneur. That is why I have supported him and continue to do so.” 

David Corker, lead lawyer in Tinkov’s case, claimed Shapps and then-foreign secretary Liz Truss were chasing headlines to look tough in the aftermath of Russia’s invasion. Per Financial Times, 19 July 2023. “Just round up the usual suspects.” That’s my impression of what Truss was doing,” he said. “Tinkov had a plane on the tarmac at Luton airport and it gave Shapps a chance to talk about yet more oligarchs’ toys.” Per Financial Times, 19 July 2023

This is the lunch prepared by the Chinese government for Henry #Kissinger. Both the food and the decorations have significant cultural meanings, and together they demonstrate great appreciation for Kissinger who once helped foster friendship between China and the United States.

🍑 A longevity peach cake. The longevity peach is a symbol of the Peaches of Immortality. These peaches, according to Chinese mythology, only come into season once every few thousand years, yet eating one will make one immortal. 

It takes the form of a peach and is typically filled with red bean paste or lotus paste; its exterior is white with a crimson dyed tip. This cake is traditionally presented on the birthdays of the elderly as a way of honoring their accomplishment of living to a ripe old age.

🌲 Crane and pine ornamentation (松鹤延年). The crane, a symbol of long life and good fortune in Chinese culture, is the most frequently depicted bird in Chinese art. As a symbol of immortality and longevity, the crane played an important role in ancient Chinese culture. 

In traditional Chinese painting, cranes are often depicted beside pine trees as a way of sending well wishes for a long and healthy life to the elderly.  Because it is evergreen and can withstand harsh winters, the pine tree is often used as a symbol of everlasting life.

🔵 Calabash ornamentation. The Chinese pronunciation of calabash (葫芦) sounds like happiness and fortune (福禄). It also stands for everlasting life and health. 

⛰️ The decoration of lush mountains and sparkling water (绿水青山). Both are representations of enduring friendship that convey hopes for peace and prosperity between China and the United States.

full_text:
The photograph capturing Alfred Hitchcock holding a pitchfork on the lawns of Pinewood Studios in Buckinghamshire, United Kingdom, on July 22, 1971, provides a glimpse into the life and career of the legendary film director, producer, and screenwriter. 

Alfred Hitchcock, born on August 13, 1899, in Leytonstone, Essex, England, is widely regarded as one of the greatest filmmakers in the history of cinema. Known for his distinctive style and innovative storytelling techniques, Hitchcock's contributions to the suspense and thriller genres have left an indelible mark on film.

By 1971, Hitchcock was already a highly celebrated director, having directed numerous iconic films throughout his career. Some of his most renowned works include "Psycho" (1960), "Vertigo" (1958), "North by Northwest" (1959), and "Rear Window" (1954), among many others. His films often featured themes of suspense, psychological tension, and dark humor, showcasing his mastery of building suspense and creating unforgettable cinematic experiences.

Pinewood Studios, where the photograph was taken, is a major film and television production studio located in Buckinghamshire, England. Established in 1935, Pinewood Studios has been the backdrop for countless films, including many of Hitchcock's productions. The studio has a rich history and continues to be a prominent hub for the British and international film industry.

The image of Alfred Hitchcock holding a pitchfork offers a glimpse into his unique personality and the way he blended his public image with his cinematic work. Hitchcock was known for making cameo appearances in his films, and he often made playful and unexpected appearances in public events, which became part of his personal brand. The photograph captured during the filming of "Frenzy" (1972), Hitchcock's penultimate film, showcases his penchant for merging his persona with his art, adding an element of intrigue and playfulness to his public image.

"On this occasion, I want to express my heartfelt gratitude to the Romanian people for the assistance provided to Ukrainians who fled from the war to Romania, to the Romanians who welcomed them with open arms, and to those who are helping Ukraine and the Ukrainian people in these extremely difficult times." 

These are two of the most important messages that His Excellency wanted to convey to you. 

I was invited alongside @flavia_boghiu, the Deputy Mayor of Brasov, who organized the most comprehensive center for Ukrainians affected by the fate brought upon them by Russia's unjust war against Ukraine, at the Embassy of Ukraine in Romania/Посольство України в Румунії. 

Each of us received a certificate of appreciation for what we have attempted and achieved in helping Ukraine and the Ukrainians who are truly in need of assistance. She is here, and I am there. 

I sincerely believe that this certificate of appreciation belongs to all of you. Without false modesty, nothing of what "I have managed to do" in and for Ukraine would have been possible without you. So this is a certificate of appreciation for "all of you, and what we all managed to do togheter". Those here, those who have helped Ukrainians in need (I emphasize this), and those who have shown empathy, understanding, and compassion! Humanity. 

When I told His Excellency that there are pensioners who donate, he indicated that he knows and appreciates the effort of each one of you, both from here and from all over Romania! 

Flavia Boghiu, the Deputy Mayor, thanks the people of Brasov, the hundreds of volunteers from the CATTIA center, and the institutions in Brasov that got involved in the humanitarian crisis generated by Russia's invasion. 

I am proud of what we manage to do together! It's about saving lives, easing suffering, and humanity. It's about what we would want to feel if we were in the same situation as them. 

As it is written on the certificate: 

#SlavaUkraini! Glory to Romania! Glory to the Heroes!

full_text:
#24YEARSOFKARGILWAR ….No man left behind is an ethos of the Indian Army. This conduct is a part of our military training and value system..unlike Pakistan who during Kargil War refused to take back the  mortal remains of their own soldiers.
So much so, that the last rites of the Pakistani soldiers were carried out by us as per their religion. 

I am reminded of one such incident, during #TigerHill battle. On 5thJul 99, during the fire fight, the body of Gdr Rattan Chand who was part of Ghatak Team fell a thousand feet into an icy crevice. Despite our best efforts, we could not locate the body for many days because of difficult and jaggered slopes of the terrain . 

The pressure of retrieving his body kept mounting on me  as I worried about how I would face his wife, children, parents and even my own troops. I prayed to God and continued the search despite all odds. It was after five days of relentless searching, that the special team of Ghatak commandos could retrieve his body on 15 th July 99 and handed it over to his family who were staying put at Udhampur waiting. The loss was irreparable but as a CO ,I felt content, that the brave soldier would be laid to rest in presence of his family. I could live up to age old ethos of leaving no man behind. 
#JaiHind
